===Etymology 1===
{{ja-kanjitab|гҒҸгҒҳгӮү|yomi=k}}
{{IPAchar|/kudira/}} вҶ’ {{IPAchar|/kudНЎК‘ira/}}

From {{inh|ja|ojp|-}}.  Appears in the ''{{w|Kojiki}}'' of 712 CE with the {{w|man'yЕҚgana}} spelling {{m|ja||д№…жІ»иүҜ|tr=kudira}}. Hypothesized as ultimately from reconstructed {{inh|ja|jpx-pro|*kuntira}}.

Ultimate derivation unclear. Theories include an alteration from {{ja-l|еҸЈ}}{{ja-l|еәғ}} (''kuchibiro'') in reference to the wide mouth;<ref>'''1891''', иЁҖжө· (''Genkai'', вҖңSea of WordsвҖқ) (in Japanese), lead editor {{w|ЕҢtsuki Fumihiko}}.  Entry available online [http://www.babelbible.net/genkai/genkai.cgi?mode=right&imode=0&noexpand=0&page=281 here].</ref> an alteration from {{ja-l|еҸЈ}}{{ja-l|й–ӢгҒҸ}} (''kuchibiraku'') in reference to the gaping mouth; and an alteration from {{ja-l|й»’зҷҪ}} (''kuroshiro'') in reference to the black-and-white coloration of certain [[cetacean]]s.<ref>'''2007-2014''', ж—Ҙжң¬иҫһе…ё (''Nihon Jiten'', вҖңJapan DictionaryвҖқ), з”ҹзү©иӘһжәҗиҫһе…ё (''Seibutsu Gogen Jiten'', вҖңLiving Organism Etymology DictionaryвҖқ) section (in Japanese).  Entry available online [http://www.nihonjiten.com/data/45904.html here].</ref>

However, the oldest sources clearly spell the term as ''kudira''.
* This rules out {{m|ja|еҸЈ|tr=kuti вҶ’ kuchi||mouth}} as an [[etymon]], as the oldest compounds using this term use the bound form ''kutu'', not ''kuti'', and there is no support for a ''kutu'' вҶ’ ''kudi'' shift.
* This also rules out {{m|ja|зҷҪ|tr=siro, sira вҶ’ shiro, shira||white}} as an [[etymon]].  Although [[rendaku]] (voicing in compounds) would give modern ''jira'' as a reading for {{m|ja|зҷҪ}}, the ancient reading of ''sira'' would voice to something closer to ''zira'', and there is no support for a ''zira'' вҶ’ ''dira'' shift.

Also compare {{cog|ko|кі лһҳ}} "whale."

